         <div type="poem"
              xml:id="txt_GrayTh1716_epww"
              corresp="authors.xml#txt_GrayTh1716_epww"
              subtype="eceptext"
              rendition="#lgindent"
              rhyme="abab"
              met="-+|-+|-+|-+|-+/"
              n="10"
              ana="#iamb #pentameter">
            <link type="author" target="authors.xml#aut_GrayTh1716"/>
            <head>[Epitaph on Sir William Williams]</head>
            <lg>
               <l n="1">Here, foremost in the dangerous paths of fame,</l>
               <l n="2">Young Williams fought for England's fair renown;</l>
               <l n="3">His mind each Muse, each Grace adorned his frame,</l>
               <l n="4">Nor Envy dared to view him with a frown.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg>
               <l n="5">At Aix uncalled his maiden sword he drew,</l>
               <l n="6">(There first in blood his infant glory sealed);</l>
               <l n="7">From fortune, pleasure, science, love, he flew,</l>
               <l n="8">And scorned repose when Britain took the field.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg>
               <l n="9">With eyes of flame and cool intrepid breast,</l>
               <l n="10">Victor he stood on Belle Isle's rocky steeps;</l>
               <l n="11">Ah gallant youth! this marble tells the rest,</l>
               <l n="12">Where melancholy Friendship bends and weeps.</l>
            </lg>
         </div>
